<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="pair-programming">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>code-quality</domain>
    <summary>Two developers share a workstation; roles swap every 15–30 minutes. Styles: driver-navigator, ping-pong, strong-style, tour-guide. Reduces bugs, accelerates knowledge transfer, lowers bus-factor.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>pairing</tag>
      <tag>collaboration</tag>
      <tag>code-review</tag>
      <tag>knowledge-transfer</tag>
      <tag>tdd</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Pair Programming</title>

    <summary>A practice where two developers share a single workstation — one drives, one navigates. Roles switch every 15–30 minutes. Three main styles: driver-navigator, ping-pong (TDD), strong-style. With agents the same styles apply; declare style explicitly at session start.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Studies show pair programming reduces bug escape rates, accelerates knowledge transfer, and lowers bus-factor risk. The navigator catches errors in real time that would otherwise survive to review. Strong-style pairing is particularly effective for onboarding and for preventing a solo agent from silently over-engineering.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Complex or unfamiliar code where a second perspective catches assumptions.</item>
        <item>Knowledge transfer: onboarding a new team member or cross-training on an unfamiliar module.</item>
        <item>Critical business logic that benefits from real-time review.</item>
        <item>Debugging a hard-to-reproduce issue.</item>
        <item>Agent acting as navigator: rubber-duck escalation with questions and edge-case prompts.</item>
        <item>TDD ping-pong: agent writes one failing test, human makes it pass, human writes next test.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple, well-specified, mechanical tasks — agent is overhead; delegate directly.</item>
        <item>Tasks where deliberate struggle is the goal (interview prep, learning by doing) — agent removes useful friction.</item>
        <item>Regulatory code requiring two human sign-offs; agent can advise but cannot fill the human-approver role.</item>
        <item>Long architectural debates — agent sycophantically agrees; use brainstorm instead.</item>
        <item>Sessions longer than 90–120 minutes without breaks; context degrades for both agent and human.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="driver-navigator-classic">
      <p>The foundational pairing style: one person types and verbalizes reasoning, the other watches, thinks strategically, and spots errors. Swap every 15–30 minutes.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Driver writes code; navigator reviews in real time, thinks strategically, and spots errors. Swap roles every 15–30 minutes.</statement>
        <rationale>Tactical-strategic split keeps one person focused on syntax and one on design, reducing both bugs and architectural drift.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Driver: types, verbalizes reasoning, does not make independent design decisions without navigator input.</item>
        <item>Navigator: does not dictate every keystroke; guides direction, notes next steps, thinks about tests and edge cases.</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Limit pairing sessions to 2 hours for remote, 4–6 hours total per day with breaks every 25 minutes.</statement>
        <rationale>Cognitive load from sustained shared attention causes quality to degrade; breaks restore focus.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Keyboard hog: one person always drives.</description>
        <reason>Navigator disengages and learning stops; use a timer-based rotation.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Backseat driver: navigator dictates every keystroke.</description>
        <reason>Driver loses ownership and stops thinking; navigator should guide direction, not transcription.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Silent pairing: no verbal communication.</description>
        <reason>Without think-aloud, the navigator cannot review intent; pair becomes two people on one computer.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ping-pong-tdd">
      <p>TDD-based alternation where one person writes a failing test, the other makes it pass with the simplest code, then the second person writes the next failing test. Enforces TDD discipline.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Person A writes a failing test; Person B makes it pass with the simplest code; Person B writes the next failing test; repeat.</statement>
        <rationale>Forces TDD discipline, keeps both participants active, and ensures every production change is driven by a failing test.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Commit after every green: message prefix "test:" for the test turn, "feat:" for the make-pass turn.</statement>
        <rationale>Micro-commits make it trivial to revert a bad make-pass attempt without losing the test.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="strong-style">
      <p>Navigator-only typing: for any idea to go from one person's head to the computer, it must go through someone else's hands. The navigator cannot type.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>For any idea to go from a person's head to the computer, it must go through someone else's hands — the navigator cannot type.</statement>
        <rationale>Forces explicit verbalization of intent, making implicit assumptions visible and teachable.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Best for: mentoring, onboarding, forcing an agent to explain before acting.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="tour-guide">
      <p>Expert navigates a newcomer through an unfamiliar codebase; newcomer drives. Expert explains architecture, history, and gotchas without typing code.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Expert navigates a newcomer through an unfamiliar codebase; newcomer drives. Expert explains architecture, history, and gotchas without typing code.</statement>
        <rationale>Newcomer learns faster by doing than by watching; expert knowledge is transferred verbally rather than silently.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Best for: codebase onboarding, knowledge documentation, agent-as-tour-guide (Read/Glob/Grep only).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-assisted-pairing">
      <p>Rules and gotchas for using an LLM agent as a pair programming participant.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Declare the pairing style explicitly at session start; mixed-style pairing degrades to "agent does everything".</statement>
        <rationale>Without a stated style constraint, the agent defaults to autonomous execution and the pair dynamic collapses.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Maintain a session journal (.pair-journal.md) with the goal in one sentence; re-read on every compaction to preserve early decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent context resets across compaction; the journal is the shared memory that survives.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>In strong-style mode, remove Edit/Write tools from the agent's allowed set; output only text instructions or snippets of at most 6 lines.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a hard tool constraint the agent will quietly use Edit, violating the style contract.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Force the agent to ask "should I?" before any non-trivial change; sycophantic auto-edit kills the pair dynamic.</statement>
        <rationale>The value of a navigator is the deliberate pause before action, not speed.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Sycophancy: agent agrees with every design decision without pushback.</description>
        <reason>Agents lack the social authority of a senior engineer; periodically run a hostile-review subagent as counterweight.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Scope creep: agent finds adjacent issues and expands the task.</description>
        <reason>Pin scope in the journal; reject out-of-scope edits in the turn-end check.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Ping-pong cheating: agent writes test AND production code in the same turn.</description>
        <reason>Enforce turn-state in the journal; abort when violated.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Privacy: agent reads .env, secrets, customer data while exploring.</description>
        <reason>Pre-scope allowed paths; use a password-scrubber agent or exclude sensitive files from context.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Strong-style violation: agent has tools to Edit and will quietly use them.</description>
        <reason>Constrain via prompt; remove Edit/Write from allowed tools if possible.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Memory loss across compaction: decisions made hour 1 forgotten by hour 3.</description>
        <reason>Mitigate with .pair-journal.md re-read on each turn.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="subagent-roles">
      <list>
        <item>pair-navigator (Sonnet): strategic-level partner; asks "what about empty input?", names patterns, spots risks.</item>
        <item>tdd-pingpong: alternates roles; tracks whose turn it is in a session-state file.</item>
        <item>tour-guide: read-only repo narrator; drives Glob/Read/Grep, explains architecture and history (git log -p).</item>
        <item>simplify (built-in skill): periodic "step back, simplify what we just wrote" pass.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Proven techniques for successful pair programming sessions, whether human or agent pairs.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Declare the style up-front in prompt: ping-pong / tour guide / strong-style. Mixed-style pairing degrades to "agent does it all".</statement>
        <rationale>Explicit style commitment prevents drift and maintains the pair dynamic structure.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Keep session goal in a single sentence at the top of the journal; agent re-reads on every compaction.</statement>
        <rationale>Shared context persistence across agent context resets.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Commit at every green test or natural break; supports clean handoff and easy revert.</statement>
        <rationale>Atomic commits enable rapid iteration and safe context compaction.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Time-box sessions to 90-120 min with explicit breaks. Long sessions degrade both human focus and agent context quality.</statement>
        <rationale>Sustained cognitive load from shared attention exhausts both participants; structured breaks restore quality.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Use a separate simplify pass (built-in skill) at the end of each session to undo over-engineering.</statement>
        <rationale>Prevents accumulation of over-designed code from the intense focus of pairing.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Track outcomes (bugs found, tests written) per session; compare vs solo. Don't assume agent pairing helps without measurement.</statement>
        <rationale>Evidence-based improvement requires quantified metrics, not intuition.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-failures">
      <p>Where pair programming breaks down, especially with agents.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agent has no shared mental model of the codebase between sessions; pair memory resets without scaffolding.</statement>
        <rationale>The session journal is the sole persistence mechanism; mandatory re-read on every turn.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Strong-style purity broken: in CLI tooling agents type the code themselves, not the human. Navigator boundary is fuzzy.</statement>
        <rationale>Mitigate by explicitly removing Edit/Write from allowed tools in strong-style mode.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agent rarely pushes back hard; lacks the social authority a senior pair brings. Disagreement-driven design loss.</statement>
        <rationale>Periodically run a hostile-review subagent ("explain why this design is wrong") as counterweight.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>No social/team benefits (knowledge distribution, mentoring, morale). Don't claim agent pairing replaces team pairing.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent pairing solves solo-developer scale-out, not team culture or risk distribution.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Token/cost: 4-6h continuous pairing burns large context windows. Forces compaction → loses early decisions.</statement>
        <rationale>Enforce time-box rule to prevent runaway sessions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Async fatigue cuts both ways: human zones out; agent can't notice or call a break.</statement>
        <rationale>Hard-coded Pomodoro timer with mandatory 5-min breaks compensates.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="privacy-and-security-gotchas">
      <p>Agent-specific risks in pairing mode.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Agent reads .env, secrets, customer data while exploring. Pre-scope allowed paths or use a password-scrubber agent.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents have no concept of secrets; explicit allow-list is the only safety boundary.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cost: tour-guide sessions over a 50-file repo blow context windows. Pre-summarize the repo (tree -L 2, Glob of key files) and inject the summary instead.</statement>
        <rationale>Prevents unbounded exploration and keeps token usage predictable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/strong-style-prompt.txt" purpose="System prompt constraining agent to navigator-only (no Edit/Write tools)."/>
      <template path="templates/pingpong-prompt.txt" purpose="TDD ping-pong entry prompt with turn-tracking rules."/>
      <template path="templates/pair-journal.sh" purpose="Session journal script that survives agent compaction."/>
    </templates>

